> <<[Fountainhead parody] I hope you enjoy reading it.>>
>     Yes, very much.  And it answered one question I'd had about a
> particular concession that I thought the movie probably made to Hollywood
> sensibilities, despite of Ayn Rand.  In the movie, the relationship between
> Dominique and Howard R. is presented as if, on two occasions, they get
> teasingly close to each other but never consummate a sexual relationship.
> It was my guess that the book is much less restrained in that regard, which
> your parody certainly suggests.  

Dominique Francon and Roark have a full (and secret) affair in the book. 

> But the movie doesn't really convey any 
> impression that Dominique is particularly a free-living (and free-loving)
> woman, which your parody certainly suggests. 

Actually, Dominique in my parody is quite akin to the Friends' character that 
is associated with it. You may also notice that I very soon liberated her 
from much of the psychological jail she placed herself into in the book. In 
the book, she was very much not a free-living character.

> So, it certainly appears that 
> the movie extremely tames down the sexual aspects of the book.  If they
> remade it today, it would no doubt be much steamier.

Possibly.

